               <head>Poetical texts in Persian</head>
               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070315">
                  <summary>Poems in Persian, in Hebrew characters.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="jpr" otherLangs="he" />
                  <msItem>
                     <locus from="1r" to="349v" />
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="en" key="viaf_36790053 viaf.org/viaf/36790053">Shahin</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="he" key="viaf_36790053 viaf.org/viaf/36790053">שאהין</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="en">Poems</title>
                     <title xml:lang="he">שירים</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>Persian poems embodying the narrative of the Pentateuch. The volume begins with
                  dedicatory poems, then follows Genesis (f. 5r), and Exodus (f. 168r). The
                  remaining portions are not marked.</p>
                        <p>F. 348 contains (in a different hand) a duplicate of a portion of Genesis.</p>
                        <p>A number of Persian stanzas with Hebrew headings, f. 2r.</p>
                        <p>A piyuṭ of Eliyah ben Binyamin ha-Leṿi, f. 347v.</p>
                        <p>The colophons seem to have been written in a different, possibly later, hand than
                  the main scribe. The later scribe may be identified with the writer of the short
                  note on page 323a (Khudādād ben Mūsā; כדאדאד בן מוצא), although a closer
                  paleographical examination is required. The second colophon states that the scribe
                  of “the Book of Shāhīn” is deceased. Interestingly, the name of the scribe
                  mentioned in this colophon is Amīnā, which happen to be the pen-name of the Jewish
                  poet Benjamin ben Mishael of Kāshān (1672/73 - after 1732/33). The date of copying
                  (1702) makes it possible that Shāhīn's work was indeed copied by Benjamin ben
                  Mishael in the city of Kāshān. However, there is always the possibility that a
                  later scribe attributed this manuscript to Amīnā in order to increase its
                  value. (Information provided by Ofir Haim.)</p>
                     </note>
                     <colophon xml:lang="jpr">שנת התסב נוישתה שוד כה אדר הצעיר עבד יי<locus n="167r" />
                     </colophon>
                     <colophon xml:lang="jpr">תמאם שד אין כתאב שאהין בסדת חקיר ופקיר החכם השלם מ' אמינה ע"ה
                דר רוז ג' שבת כ"ה במאה סיון שנת התסב ליצירה אלאהי אמיד וארם כה מבארך באשנד בר כאננדה
                גאן אין כתאב ובר נויסנדה א'נ'ס'ה' א'ו'י'ר תם'.<locus n="347v" />
                     </colophon>
                  </msItem>
